\section{$(C,\theta)$-spacings}\label{space_sec}

In order to prove Theorem~\ref{length} it is necessary to produce, for each $x\in{\ensuremath{\mathbb{S}}}^2$, two foliations through $x$ (with leafable leaves) that evolve to be nearly perpendicular.  In this section we show that for each Jordan curve there is a scale so that this can be done.  Here, scale refers to the constant $C>0$ in the definition of leafable.

In what follows we denote the antipodal map by $a$ and write $\overline{xy}$ for the unique great circle containing non-antipodal points $x$ and $y$.  

\begin{defn}\label{spacing} [$(C,\theta)$-spacing] Given a Jordan curve  $\gamma$ on ${\ensuremath{\mathbb{S}}}^2$ and constants $C>0$ and $0<\theta<\frac{\pi}{2}$ we say that a set of points $\{y_1,y_2,\ldots, y_n\}$ is a {\it $(C,\theta)$-spacing} for $\gamma$ if
\begin{enumerate}
\item $\overline{B_C(y_i)\cup B_C(ay_i)}\cap\gamma=\varnothing$ for each $i=1,\ldots,n$
\item For each $x\in{\ensuremath{\mathbb{S}}}^2$ there exists $i_1,i_2$ such that the angle between the great circles 
$\overline{xy_{i_1}}$ and $\overline{xy_{i_2}}$ is greater than $\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta$.
\end{enumerate}
\end{defn}

\begin{lemma} \label{ex_space} Let $\gamma$ be a Jordan curve on ${\ensuremath{\mathbb{S}}}^2$. For each $0<\theta<\frac{\pi}{2}$ there exists $C>0$ such that a $(C,\theta)$-spacing exists for $\gamma$.
\end{lemma}

